keywords = "public extension system",
keywords = "private sector ",
abstract = "This case study analyzes how an output aggregator provides extension to the farmers who are under its contract. Using a sugarcane processing company in southern India, \{EID\} Parry, this chapter shows how the company is able to maintain both the quantity and quality of cane procured from the farmers. It also shows how local innovation brings various service providers to play an integrated role: The company is able to apply a one-stop approach to its advisory services. Results indicate that the extension service provided by the company is necessitated by two key factors: slow withdrawal of the public extension system from the farmers under contract with the company and the need to maintain the quantity of supply to the processing industry. Further, other environmental factors such as moving away from sugarcane by the farmers to cashews and low availability of groundwater have created challenges for cane growers. To entice farmers to stay in sugarcane farming, the company focused on removing these constraints and making sugarcane production hassle free for the farmers. This resulted in a win–win situation for both the farmers and the sugarcane crushing company. "
