abstract = "Publisher Summary The substantial increase in food consumption is attributed to a combination of economic growth, increased use of irrigated land, long-term declines in food prices, and rapid growth of imports from developed economies. This chapter discusses the changes in food consumption pattern. The study of consumption patterns is important for a number of reasons. First, since total consumption accounts for more than two-thirds of national income in many countries, it is the largest macroeconomic aggregate, having great significance for the state of the economy as a whole and business conditions. Second, the pattern of consumption contains useful information regarding economic welfare and living standards and, thus, is an objective way of measuring and assessing economic performance. Finally, understanding the price responsiveness of consumption is critical for a number of microeconomic policy issues, which include the measurement of distortions, optimal taxation, and the treatment of externalities. "
}
@incollection{Babu200989,
