doi = "http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/B978-0-12-374712-9.00010-9",
url = "http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9780123747129000109",
author = "Suresh C. Babu and Prabuddha Sanyal",
abstract = "Publisher Summary This chapter briefly discusses maternal education and community characteristics as indicators of nutritional status of children. The literature on the welfare of children in developing countries emphasizes the importance of having literate parents and, in particular, of having a literate mother. The nutritional status of children is enhanced by having better-educated parents, especially the mother. There are both immediate causes of poor health and nutrition, such as lack of access to food, low utilization of health facilities or the poor quality of these facilities, and the underlying factors such as family income and educational status that cause it. The mechanism through which maternal education affects child health is quite complex (whether through higher wages, better health knowledge, greater child care, or improving the health environment in reducing mortality rates) and thus it requires a thorough analysis. The purpose of this chapter is to examine the pathways through which maternal education improves child health and to understand the impact of community characteristics (such as presence of hospitals and better water and sanitation conditions) on weight for age and height for age using a multivariate regression model that controls for other individual characteristics such as child's age. "
}
@incollection{Babu2009279,
