abstract = "Countries faced with production instability must translate that instability into stock, trade, or consumption variability. Yet governments typically want to stabilize consumption and minimize imports at low cost. Optimizing models are used here to describe efficient policy interventions for meeting these objectives and to measure trade-offs between them. Lessons learned from the optimal policies are then applied to simple price band/buffer stock policies in order to design a simple yet efficient policy. Pakistan and Kenya provide contrasting examples because of differences in production instability and the desire to minimize imports. Nevertheless, conclusions are robust across the two countries. "
