author = "Julie Babinard and Timothy Josling",
abstract = "Publisher Summary This chapter describes the role of various stakeholders and groups in mobilizing public opinion, implementing regulatory control, and developing market for the genetically modified organisms (GMO). The debate on \{GMO\} is intense as there are significant economic stakes for private firms that market this technology and significant political stakes for non-governmental organizations (NGOs) that oppose its use. Government agencies and scientific researchers also have considerable interest in the outcome of the debate, and one would not expect them to be neutral observers. The main protagonists in the debate include the firms which are developing and introducing the new technology, the corporations that market and process the crops, and those that sell the food at retail. They are joined by a various consumer and environmental groups, who often pool ideas and collaborate to slow down their implementation. Government departments and food and environmental agencies are also players in the game, as are international bureaucrats. Somewhere caught in the middle are farmers, cautious about growing crops that some consumers mistrust but eager to adopt cost-saving technology, particularly if it is available to competitors; consumers bewildered by the variety of opinions emanating from public and private agencies; and developing country governments concerned with the perceived over-regulation or oligopolistic control of the technology. "
